<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Malaprop wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Rain spells only hit for two waves if more than one critter are under the rain.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Working as intended. A rain can only hit a maximum of 4 times, for a maximum of 3 waves. 
<br />

<br />
1 target = 3 hits, 3 waves 
<br />
2 targets = 4 hits, 2 waves (2 per mob) 
<br />
3 targets = 4 hits, 2 waves (2 on one mob, 1 on the other two) 
<br />
4 targets = 4 hits, 1 wave (1 hit per mob)
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Mind Wrack Recourse overwrites Elemental Draw and Elemental Siphon</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Working as intended.
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Bagoftricks wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Shared health won't trigger if the pet isn't right next to you.
<br />

<br />
You have no protection if you send your pet to fight and get summoned, which is the only real use I see for that ability.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Working as intended. Shared Health is /shield, and will not work outside its range.
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>kshipper wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Pet doesn't always enrage on low health which can really screw you up if you are counting on a heal to land during the enrage part.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
This can happen for one of three reasons:
<br />
1. The enrage timer isn't reset
<br />
2. Your pet gets stunned when its supposed to enrage. This happens to some NPCs too
<br />
3. Your pet receives enough damage in one hit to outright kill the pet.
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>itchyban wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Certain spells, especially rains, give "out of range" messages when they shouldn't, probably due to z-axis differences.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Courtesy of Andara:
<br />
This isn't a bug, it's a feature of the distance programming in the game.  Consider this:
<br />
<img src="http://members.rogers.com/shadowedblade/nukerange.jpg" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
Where each elipse is the outer surface of a sphere, the radius of the sphere (n) is the distance a magician can nuke and each black dot on the outer sphere represents a mob.
<br />

<br />
You think you can't nuke as far from the mob below you because it isn't as close to you in the x and y directions, but it really is just as close.
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Oben wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I couldn't get two different dpoc focused Rathe's Sons to equip weapons </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
You probably summoned a focused pet, then gave him a suit of phantom plate before you gave him armor. That will cause you to fill up your pet's limited inventory and thus make him refuse to equip weapons. Don't give focused pets phantom plate, they already have it.</span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by Guest on Thu Sep 23, 2004 1:52 pm; edited 5 times in total</span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
